{"cursor":"7555","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox mineral\n| name = Plagioclase category = Feldspar mineral group, tectosilicate boxwidth =\n| boxbgcolor = image = Plagioklas1.jpg imagesize = caption = A photomicrograph\n| of a plagioclase crystal under cross polarized light. The plagioclase crystal\n| shows a distinct banding effect called a Polysynthetic twinning. formula =\n| NaAlSi 3O 8 â CaAl 2Si 2O 8\n| symmetry = Triclinic pinacoidal H-M symbol: () Space group: C color =\n| White, gray, bluish white, reddish white, greenish white habit = Massive to\n| granular system = Triclinic twinning = Common, albite law striations on\n| {001} cleavage = Good on {001} and {010} fracture = tenacity\n| = Brittle mohs = 6 - 6.5 luster = Vitreous polish = refractive = Albite:\n| n Î± 1.527, n Î² 1.532 n Î³ 1.538 Anorthite:\n| n Î± 1.577 n Î² 1.585 n Î³ 1.590\n| opticalprop = Biaxial (+) albite, biaxial (-) anorthite\n| birefringence = dispersion = pleochroism = fluorescence= absorption = streak =\n| White gravity = 2.62 (albite) to 2.76 (anorthite) Klein,\n| Cornelis and Cornelius S. Hurbut, Jr.; Manual of Mineralogy, Wiley, 20th ed.,\n| 1980, pp.454-456 ISBN 0-471-80580-7  density = melt = fusibility =\n| diagnostic = solubility = Albite insoluble in HCl, anorthite decomposed by HCl\n|  diaphaneity = Transparent to translucent other = references\n| = [http://webmineral.com/data/Plagioclase.shtml Webmineral\n| data] \n}}\n\n. (unknown scale)]] rocks, fine-grained plagioclase can display a 'microlitic'\n  texture of many small crystals.]]\n\n'Plagioclase' is an important series of tectosilicate minerals within the\nfeldspar family. Rather than referring to a particular mineral with a specific\nchemical composition, plagioclase is a solid solution series, more properly\nknown as the 'plagioclase feldspar' series (from the Greek \"oblique fracture\",\nin reference to its two cleavage angles). This was first shown by the German\nmineralogist Johann Friedrich Christian Hessel (1796â1872) in 1826. The series\nranges from albite to anorthite endmembers (with respective compositions\nNaAlSi 3O 8 to CaAl 2Si 2O 8),\nwhere sodium and calcium atoms can substitute for each other in the mineral's\ncrystal lattice structure. Plagioclase in hand samples is often identified by\nits polysynthetic twinning or 'record-groove' effect.\n\nPlagioclase is a major constituent mineral in the Earth's crust, and is\nconsequently an important diagnostic tool in petrology for identifying the\ncomposition, origin and evolution of igneous rocks. Plagioclase is also a major\nconstituent of rock in the highlands of the Earth's moon.\n","linknr":240,"url":"Plagioclase_feldspar","recorded":1374761902,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Plagioclase&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Plagioclase&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Plagioclase","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","/w/index.php?title=Plagioclase_feldspar&redirect=no","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/File:Plagioklas1.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b3/Plagioklas1.jpg/240px-Plagioklas1.jpg","/wiki/Feldspar","/wiki/Tectosilicate","/wiki/Chemical_formula","/wiki/Hermann%E2%80%93Mauguin_notation","/wiki/H-M_symbol","/wiki/Space_group","/wiki/Crystal_habi